comments.body:
It appears that AWS/EC2 metrics are put in with single dimensions.  A data point that would represent something like
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {ImageId=emi-3C073728,InstanceId=i-49D94300,InstanceType=m1.small}, instead gets inserted separately as

CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {ImageId=emi-3C073728}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {InstanceId=i-49D94300}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {InstanceType=m1.small}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {}

Under the hood we do this anyway, but also insert it as
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {ImageId=emi-3C073728,InstanceId=i-49D94300}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {ImageId=emi-3C073728,InstanceType=m1.small}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {InstanceId=i-49D94300,InstanceType=m1.small}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {ImageId=emi-3C073728,InstanceId=i-49D94300,InstanceType=m1.small}

The correct way to fix this is to put in the exact points that amazon does, but for now, we will simply list the former metrics.
List-metrics after a data point from CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {ImageId=emi-3C073728,InstanceId=i-49D94300,InstanceType=m1.small} will now 
contribute
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {ImageId=emi-3C073728}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {InstanceId=i-49D94300}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {InstanceType=m1.small}
CPUUtilization  AWS/EC2 {}

(Just the single dimension, and zero-dimension case).  This is only true for AWS/EC2 metrics.
